Q15_1_text: Open access statistical tools (R) can be difficult for new users to feel comfortable using due to the inconsistency of syntax across commands. Q15_4_text: While I believe that computational methods can be useful, I feel that discussion of researcher positionality's effects on research outcomes is largely under-discussed. While qualitative methods (e.g., ethnographic methods, discourse analysis, etc.) generally acknowledge that a researcher's positionality shapes the choices that they make in research, which questions they ask, how they interpret results, how they present results, etc., I find that this conversation is largely absent among computational methods practitioners. These types of conversations are essential to the future of these methods in order to ensure that as researchers we do not continue to reinforce oppressive patterns in research towards marginalized populations.

Q15_1_text: There is very little knowledge about open access tools and open data. I spend a significant amount of time introducing students and colleagues to tools, such as freely available corpora. Corpus building is also very underrated as a technique in computational social sciences.
Q15_2_text: Generally there's low coding skills. Many people jump directly into the tools they want to learn, but without a certain foundation in data structures, functional coding and similar, it is common to run into vices that make learning new packages difficult.
Q15_4_text: I don't think we as a community pay enough attention to making sure validation of results is enforced throughout. Journals should have a common standard on what are acceptable validation mechanisms. For example, I get more and more papers to review that use things like LIWC and even off the shell sentiment analysis tools and then provide no validation, but yet get published because other reviewers don't see the need for this. So, in terms of training, I see our biggest shortcomings in: not training people to ask theoretically-driven and relevant questions, and not being able to validate the results of their computational analyses.

Q11_Other_text: The gold standard for most measurements is whether they map on to what expert human scorers would say. Thirdly are whether it produces theoretically-meaningful findings.
